<TITLE> Khaleda for grassroots work </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 22 (bdnews24.com) - Khaleda Zia Monday urged her party leaders and activists to work at the grassroots level to strengthen the party. She met separately with the party's former lawmakers, leaders of the front organisations and a group of retired army officers at the home of journalist Shafik Rehman Monday afternoon. For the past one week, Khaleda Zia has been meeting party leaders and workers at the Eskaton home of the former Jai Jai Din editor. "Madam told us to go to our respective constituencies and work to make the party stronger. She told us that she will nominate competent, honest and popular candidate in the next election," retired brigadier general Md Abdul Khaleque told journalists after the meeting. Khaleda Zia met 16 former officers: retired brigadier general Nasiruddin Sarwar, retired Col Md Shahjahan Miah, retired Lt Col Abdul Latif Khan, retired Lt Col AHM Ruhul Islam, retired Lt Col Badiur Rahman, retired Lt Col Abdul Quader, retired Lt Col Md Shahidullah, retired Major M Shahabuddin, retired Major Hanif Uddin Sheikh, retired Major Niaz Ahmed Jaber, retired Major M Ashrafuzzzaman, retired Major Faruque Ahmed and retired Major Said Abu Bakar Siddique. A delegation of Islami Oikya Jote (IOJ) led by its vice chairman Maulana Muhiuddin Khan and secretary general Abdul Latif Nezami also met with Khaleda Zia. Maulana Muhiuddin Khan later told journalists: "We discussed preparation for the election. The four-party alliance will participate in the election. We advised the leader (Khaleda) to quickly solve the issue of distribution of seats." BNP secretary general Khandker Delwar Hossain was present at the time. BNP leader retired wing commander Hamidullah Khan, Suraiya Akhter Chcowdhury, wife of detained former home minister Altaf Hossain Chowdhury, joint secretary general Selima Rahman, former lawmakers Rabeya Chowdhury, Khaleda Rabbani, Shirin Sultana, Fahima Hossain Jubilee and leaders of Mohila Dal and JASAS also met Khaleda. After Iftar, Khaleda Zia drove back to her Mainul Road home in the evening.
